# Clean Code Standards

> Based on Robert C. Martin's "Clean Code: A Handbook of Agile Software Craftsmanship"

## Core Principles

1. **Small** — Keep functions, classes, and modules small
2. **Well Named** — Names should state purpose clearly
3. **Organized** — Related code grouped together vertically
4. **Ordered** — Most important concepts first

---

## Naming

### Principles

- **Avoid vague names**: No `data`, `list`, `temp`, `info`
- **State the purpose**: Name reveals intent
- **One concept per word**: Choose `get` OR `fetch`, not both
- **Functions are verbs**: `calculateTotal`, `validateInput`, `sendEmail`

### Examples

```java
// ❌ BAD - Vague, uninformative
int d;
String tmp;
List<String> getData();
Object handleRequest();

// ✅ GOOD - Purpose is clear
int daysSinceCreation;
String temporaryFilePath;
List<String> fetchUserNames();
ValidationResult validateUserInput();
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const x = items.filter(i => i.flag);
const result = process(data);
function handleClick() { /* ... */ }

// ✅ GOOD
const activeItems = items.filter(item => item.isActive);
const sortedResults = sortByDate(data);
function onSubmitButtonClick() { /* ... */ }
```

### Boolean Naming

```java
// ✅ GOOD - is/has/can/should prefix
boolean isActive;
boolean hasPermission;
boolean canProceed;
boolean shouldRetry;
```

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
const isLoggedIn = user.status === 'authenticated';
const hasUnsavedChanges = this.dirty === true;
```

